	Life ban on Slovak shot putter  Bratislava, (Slovakia): Slovak shot putter Mikulas Konopka faces a life ban for a second doping offence. The Slovak athletics federation said Friday that Konopka tested positive for metandienon in an out-of-competition control.   This is his second doping offence after testing positive for the banned steroid stanozolol in 2002, when he was given a two-year ban. IAAF rules call for a life ban after a second doping violation.   The Slovak federation is expected to rule on Konopka rsquo;s case next month.   The 29-year-old Konopka won Slovakia rsquo;s first gold at the European indoor Championships last year.    
	Nadia in final  Eastbourne: Eighth seed Nadia Petrova produced a ldquo;boom-boom ending rdquo; to beat Australian Samantha Stosur 6-3, 6-3 on Friday and reach the final of the Eastbourne International tournament.  The Russian surrendered only two points in the final two games and finished off with a thundering ace to book her place in Saturday rsquo;s final of the grasscourt event against either second seed Marion Bartoli or No. 4 Agnieszka Radwanska.  Petrova, a semi-finalist here last year before having to pull out with injury, began making errors at the start of the second set and had to save two break points in the first game. Luckily for her, Stosur, who has won 22 doubles titles but none in singles, was even more error-prone and failed to convert two more break points in the seventh game.
