	Ferrer wins  Den Bosch: Top seed David Ferrer reached his first career final on grass in Den Bosch on Friday by defeating Argentine Juan Martin Del Potro 7-6, 6-1. After a tight first set mdash; in which the French Open quarter finalist saved two break points to take on a tie-break mdash; Del Potro rsquo;s resistance was broken.  ldquo;My first final on grass, it rsquo;s unbelievable, rdquo; Ferrer told reporters, after wrapping up a one-sided second set. ldquo;It rsquo;s important to play well before Wimbledon, for the confidence. rdquo;
  World No. 5 Ferrer, a winner in Valencia and runner-up in Barcelona earlier this year, goes into Saturday rsquo;s final against France rsquo;s Marc Gicquel without dropping a set all week.      
	Bernie threat  London: Formula One supremo Bernie Ecclestone has threatened to switch the British Grand Prix from Silverstone to Donington Park after 2009. quot;We are discussing the possibility of reaching an agreement with Donington to host the British Grand Prix, quot; Ecclestone said on Friday. quot;We are trying to save the British Grand Prix and we want it to be staged at a venue which befits an event of its stature. I've been in negotiations for a long time and whether or not we're going to do a deal with Donington or Silverstone, I don't know. Donington have said they are going to build everything we want. Have they got the money? Only time will tell. But I think there is more chance of Donington having the money than the BRDC, rdquo; added the Briton.
                                                                                                                                                               
